{{Robert Awards}}
[[Category:Cinema of Denmark]]
[[Category:Robert Awards]]

'''Site-specific performance''' is performance created in relation to a physical site and staged at the site itself (as opposed to a [[Parts of a theatre|theatre space]]). It often involves research of the  site prior to the performance.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Dictionary of the Theatre: Terms, Concepts, and Analysis|last=Pavis|first=Patrica|publisher=University of Toronto Press|year=1998|isbn=|location=Toronto|pages=337-338}}</ref> It is often discussed in relation to both [[Site-specific theatre|theatre]] and [[Site-specific art|visual art]] traditions.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Site-Specific Performance|last=Pearson|first=Mike|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|year=2010|isbn=978-0-230-57671-1|location=New York|pages=7}}</ref> Nick Kaye was one of the first scholars to consider site-specific performance from both theatrical and visual art perspectives in his book, ''Site-Specific Art: Performance, Place and Documentation''.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/756369595|title=Site-Specific Art: Performance, Place and Documentation|last=Nick|first=Kaye|date=2008|publisher=Routledge|isbn=0415185599|oclc=756369595}}</ref>

